\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's payoff is: 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(z(Q))-h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Microfoundations for the payoff function 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}=u_{i}(x_{i}(Q),x_{-i}(Q))-h_{i}(q_{i})+g_{i}(R_{i})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benefit 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(x_{i},x_{-i})$
\end_inset

 that the player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 internalises can incorporate pure altruism.
 In fact, this seems necessary to explain Norway's and Sweden's high contributio
ns to global public goods.
 Given that these countries only have populations of 5 million and 10 million,
 respectively, the partial internalisation of the benefits of global public
 goods can hardly account for these countries' contributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 might write as: 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})=c_{i}(q_{i})-s_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}(q_{i})$
\end_inset

 could represent the net expected political cost.
 This could on the one hand include both the opportunity cost of public
 funds and the risk that domestic political forces will discredit the government
 for some constituencies that would accuse it to not act in the national
 interest.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 could include the benefit of earning the support of citizens in favor of
 altruistic action as well as the diplomatic recognition and reputation
 internationally.
 It is then plausible that we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}'>0,c_{i}''>0,s_{i}'>0,s_{i}''<0$
\end_inset

, which would imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}''(q_{i})>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the litterature modelling the voluntary contributions of states (ref)
 it is assumed that in their decision how much to voluntarily contribute
 to GPGIs countries only consider the benefit of marginal funding to the
 GPGI and the opportunity costs of funds.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Implications-for-the opportunity costs"

\end_inset

 we will see that this would imply that the 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 is almost perfectly flat on the relevant range.
 This is why the following proposition will be of interest:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "flat costs"

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}(q_{i})=q_{i}\forall i$
\end_inset

.
