 first stage of the game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Consider the marginal benefits 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial Q}$
\end_inset

 of additional money provided the GPGI in question.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)$
\end_inset

 be the set of funding levels at which country 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is indifferent between contributing a bit more or a bit less.
 Almost surely, each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 Hence for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\in I$
\end_inset

 almost surely 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{*}(i)\cap S^{*}(j)=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 But if 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are to both contribute at the Nash equilibrium, this can only happen at
 a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q\in S^{*}(i)\cap S^{*}(j)$
\end_inset

, a set that is empty with probability 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will in the next subsection see examples of GPGIs for which several countries
